    {
      "explanation": "When you separated construction from steadier services, you were identifying sectoral heterogeneity. Different industries can react very differently to the same shock, so the mixed signals were the point, not noise.",
      "name": "Sectoral Heterogeneity"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "When you showed the shared slowdown first and then the harder-hit places, you were combining common movement with local divergence. That’s the cleanest way to explain why one state can feel both connected and uneven.",
      "name": "Common and Local Effects"
    }
  ],
  "outcomes": [
    {
      "minStrongChoices": 5,
      "narrative": "You end the briefing with a story that actually fits the state: a broad slowdown, but uneven pain across places and industries. The governor sounds informed, reporters press harder, and your numbers still hold up.",
